Nor is it more convincing to say (2) That money is barren by its nature3 for houses and other things which produce no fruits by nature, tho industry of man makes fruitful.

The other arguments are more specious, (3) That here, a thing of the same kind is repaid for a thing, and that the use of the thing, money, cannot be distinguished from the thing itself, since it consists in abusu, in getting rid of it: and therefore nothing ought to be demanded for it.

2 (4) It is said in the deci-ee of the Senate*, That though there cannot be properly usufruct of a thing which perishes in the using, yet there may be quasi usufruct of such a thing, but that it does not thereby become the property of the tenant. But this merely defines the word usufruct. Certainly that word does not properly agree with the right of usury. But it does not follow that there is no such right:
